\begin_layout Abstract
Applications such as computer graphics rendering, path planning for robotics
 and patch splitting algorithms greatly benefit from having an 
\begin_inset Formula $n-$
\end_inset

simplex that encloses a given polynomial curve.
 Probably the most common curve used for this is the Bezier curves, which
 ensure that the curve is contained inside the convex hull of its control
 points.
 However, it is known that this convex hull is not the one with smallest
 volume, causing therefore great conservatism in all the applications mentioned
 before.
 This project derives and presents the MINVO basis, a polynomial basis that
 generates the smallest 
\begin_inset Formula $n-$
\end_inset

simplex that encloses any given polynomial curve.
 Global Optimality is proven for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1,2,3,4$
\end_inset

 using Sum-Of-Squares (SOS) Programming and Moment Relaxations.
 Finally, some applications of the benefit of the use of this MINVO basis
 are also presented.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The ability to approximate the space occupied by a given polynomial curve
 with a polyhedra is crucial for many applications, and is the one that
 enables real-time processing .
 For intance, in the path planning community, a sequence of overlapping
 polyhedra is usually generated in the free space, and then the constraint
 of the trajectory being in free space can be easily enforced by imposing
 that the control points of the associated Bezier curve or B-Spline are
 inside those polyhedra (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "tordesillas2019faster,preiss2017trajectory,sahingoz2014generation"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for instance).
 This allows to obtain impose a finite number of convex contraints, instead
 of continuous constraints of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $c(x,t)\le0\;\forall t$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In the 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
My PhD research is on trajectory planning and obstacle avoidance for drones.
 For the trajectories, I use Bézier curves.
 To ensure that they do not collide with the obstacles, I generate a convex
 corridor (sequence of overlapping polyhedra) in the free space, and then
 I force the control points of the Bézier curve to be inside this convex
 corridor.
 This guarantees that the trajectories are collision free, because the Bézier
 curves have the property that the curve is completely contained in the
 convex hull of its control points.
 A video of these polyhedra is available here: 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fkkkgomkX10"
target "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fkkkgomkX10"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 However, the main 
\series bold
problem
\series default
 with this approach is that the convex hull of the control points of a Bézier
 curve is sometimes very conservative with respect to the curve itself.
 In other words, there exist other points whose convex hull also contains
 that curve, and whose volume is smaller than the volume of the convex hull
 of the Bézier control points.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Rendering
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
), since it usally allows to ensure that a trajectory is completely contained
 in a polytope by simply ensuring that the control points of the trajectory
 are inside that polytope.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The need of convex hulls of minimum volumes is They are also used in 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Benefit of using the convex hull of the control points of a cuve: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

approximates the space occupied by the curve by a finite number of points.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
==================
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
So far the only paper I have found that tries to solve the same problem
 is the reference 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "herron1989polynomial"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, which finds a global minimizer for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2$
\end_inset

, and a local minimizer for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=3$
\end_inset

.
 I would like to extend the result to higher 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, and, if possible, prove a global minimizer for higher dimensions.
 For that, I am planning to impose that the curve has to be a 
\series bold
convex combination
\series default
 of the control points 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall t$
\end_inset

.
 As the 
\series bold
volume
\series default
 is given by the 
\series bold
determinant
\series default
 of a 
\series bold
non-symmetric matrix
\series default
 whose entries are functions of the control points, this will probably lead
 to a nonconvex optimization problem with infinite constraints.
 One option is to treat it as an optimal control problem, but I think I
 can reduce it to a finite number of constraints by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Using Sum-Of-Squares (SOS), imposing that the polynomial can be expressed
 as a function of 
\series bold
positive-semidefinite matrices
\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Imposing a ad hoc structure in the polynomial to ensure it is positive,
 and then use polynomial optimization and 
\series bold
moment-SDP
\series default
 relaxations to certify global optimality.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Related work
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Probably the paper most related to the problem this project is trying to
 solve is 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "herron1989polynomial"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In that work, the authors imposed a ad-hoc form for the polynomials that
 form the basis, and then solved the optimization problem over the roots
 of those polynomials.
 They were able to find a local minimum (for that specific form of the polynomia
ls) for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n=3$
\end_inset

.
 These project goes further, and tries to find global optimal solutions
 over all possible polynomials, and for higher degrees 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A similar problem has also been studied in the hyperspectral unmixing of
 the remote sensing community, which consists of trying to find, in a given
 image pixel, the proportions (or abundances) of each macroscopic materials
 (endmembers) contained in that pixel 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "uezato2019hyperspectral"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 One way to address this problem is to find the simplex with minimum volume
 that encloses a set of points (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "hendrix2013minimum"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for instance).
 However, the fact of dealing with many data points, and not necessarily
 distributed along a polynomial curve, leads to these works to generate
 different iterative algorithms to solve it (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "rogge2006iterative,iordache2009unmixing,velez2003iterative"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for instance).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Explicar convex hull algorithms?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Other related works are 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kanazawa2014minimal"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, that gives a bound for the volume of the smallest 
\begin_inset Formula $n-$
\end_inset

simplex that encloses a given convex body.
 
\end_layout

