\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
Problem 
\series default
2: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\max_{\boldsymbol{A}}\quad\left|\underbrace{\left[\begin{array}{c}
\boldsymbol{\lambda}_{1}^{T}\\
\boldsymbol{\lambda}_{2}^{T}\\
\vdots\\
\boldsymbol{\lambda}_{n+1}^{T}
\end{array}\right]}_{:=\boldsymbol{A}}\right|
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{cc}
s.t. & \lambda_{i}(t):=\boldsymbol{\lambda}_{i}^{T}\boldsymbol{t}\ge0\quad\forall t\in[-1,1]\;,\forall i\\
 & \sum\lambda_{i}(t)=1
\end{array}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace 0.2cm
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that Problem 2 is 
\series bold
independent 
\series default
of the given polynomial.
 This means that the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}$
\end_inset

 found can be applied to all the polynomials given.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that Problem 2 is clearly nonconvex, since the objective function is
 the determinant of a non-symmetric matrix.
 Moreover, it has infinite constraints.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can use now Sum-Of-Squares programming(iff for univariate polynomials),
 let us try to rewrite the second constraint of problem 2:.
 [Theorem 5 for Pablo P].
 Defining 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\boldsymbol{t}}:=\boldsymbol{P}\boldsymbol{t}$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{t}$
\end_inset

 with all its elements flipped), 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is odd:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda_{i}(t)\ge0\;\;\forall t\in[-1,1]\iff\left\{ \begin{array}{c}
\lambda_{i}(t)=\hat{\boldsymbol{t}}^{T}\left((t+1)\boldsymbol{W}_{i}+(1-t)\boldsymbol{V}_{i}\right)\hat{\boldsymbol{t}}\\
\boldsymbol{W}_{i}\in\mathbb{S}_{+}^{\frac{n+1}{2}},\boldsymbol{V}_{i}\in\mathbb{S}_{+}^{\frac{n+1}{2}}
\end{array}\right.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
if 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is even
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda_{i}(t)\ge0\;\;\forall t\in[-1,1]\iff\left\{ \begin{array}{c}
\lambda_{i}(t)=\hat{\boldsymbol{t}}^{T}\left(\boldsymbol{W}_{i}+(t+1)(1-t)\boldsymbol{V}_{i}\right)\hat{\boldsymbol{t}}\\
\boldsymbol{W}_{i}\in\mathbb{S}_{+}^{\frac{n}{2}+1},\boldsymbol{V}_{i}\in\mathbb{S}_{+}^{\frac{n}{2}}
\end{array}\right.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{S}_{+}^{m}$
\end_inset

 denotes the positive semidefinite cone (i.e.
 the set of all symmetric positive semidefinite 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times m$
\end_inset

 matrices).
 We end up therefore with a nonconvex finite-dimensional optimization problem,
 where the decision variables are the positive semidefinite matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{W}_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{V}_{i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in[1,n+1]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Optimization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The optimization problem above has been solved using the IPOPT 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wachter2006implementation"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 nonconvex solver, through the Yalmip 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Lofberg2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 interface.
 The minimums found for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1,2,3,4$
\end_inset

 are shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:minvo_and_bernstein"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The bernstein polynomial basis is also shown for comparison.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One natural question to ask is whether the basis found consitutes a global
 minimizer for problem.
 To answer this problem, we can make use of Lasserre's moment method 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "lasserre2001"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 By increasing the order of the moment relaxation, one can find tighter
 lower bounds of the original nonconvex polynomial optimization problem.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note also that any permutation of rows of A will also be a global minimizer
 for the problem.
 In other words, if 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
lambda_i is the distance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note how all the colums of A sum up to 1.
 
\end_layout

