\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Box Boxed
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
thickness "0.4pt"
separation "3pt"
shadowsize "4pt"
framecolor "black"
backgroundcolor "none"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Let us define the parametric curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}(t):=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
p_{1}(t) & \cdots & p_{n}(t)\end{array}\right]^{T}\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}(t)$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{th}$
\end_inset

-degree polynomial, with 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 Find 
\begin_inset Formula $n+1$
\end_inset

 points in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 such that the convex hull of those points contains 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}(t)$
\end_inset

 and has minimum volume.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset VSpace 0.2cm
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2$
\end_inset

, this problem tries to find the triangle with the smallest area that contains
 the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\begin{array}{cc}
x(t) & y(t)\end{array}\right]^{T}$
\end_inset

 (both 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{nd}$
\end_inset

-deg polynomials).
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $n=3$
\end_inset

, it tries to find the tetrahedron with the smallest volume that contains
 the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
x(t) & y(t) & z(t)\end{array}\right]^{T}$
\end_inset

(all 
\begin_inset Formula $3^{rd}$
\end_inset

-deg polynomials).
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Conclusions and Future Work
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The exciting results of this project can naturally lead to the following
 questions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Does there exist a closed-form solution for any degree 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Does there exist a recursivity formula to obtain the solution of problem
 3 for 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 given the previous solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $1:n-1$
\end_inset

? Will this recursivity formula allow to easily prove global optimality
 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Conclusions and Future Work
\end_layout

